Botswana’s Choppies plans to treble its stores in Kenya over the next three years, the retailer’s chief executive told Reuters on Tuesday. “We are looking at 20 to 25 new stores in the next three years time,” Choppies chief executive Ramachandran (Ram) Ottapathu said in a telephonic interview, adding that the company has 11 stores in Kenya. Read: Shoprite prepares Kenya entry to fill gaps left by Nakumatt But Ottapathu said the company was not in talks about taking over leases from Kenya’s Nakumatt, which filed for bankruptcy on Monday. Read: Kenya’s Nakumatt files for administration